=20

Hello Maureen,

=20

We received your EAS user request, and we are so excited you are looking
forward to doing some email archiving! I wanted to offer you a brief
look ahead at what is happening with EAS and email archiving at Harvard
over the next two years, and then we can plan on the next steps.=20

=20

Though we cannot yet formally announce it, we have just been awarded a
grant to move forward with a collaboration with Stanford University and
the University of Manchester to add preservation packaging functionality
into ePADD <https://library.stanford.edu/projects/epadd> , an
open-source email archiving tool originally developed by Stanford. The
collaboration is a result of our efforts to combine the functionality of
both Harvard's EAS and Stanford's ePADD tool to minimize needless
overlap of function between the two and create a more cohesive tool
overall. The development of this functionality will happen over the next
year and a half (2021-2022), and subsequently we will decommission EAS
and adopt the enhanced ePADD product - though this will not occur until
at least mid-2022. Now that we know we can move forward on this project,
we will be holding an open meeting early in 2021 elaborating on this
roadmap.

=20

While LTS resources will not be focused on enhancing EAS because it will
only be hosted for two more years, it will absolutely be supported and
maintained until it can be decommissioned, to facilitate the processing
and preservation of critical records at Harvard Library. Equipped with a
clear idea of our development path forward, our next step will be
onboarding any users/units that need it. This has presented more of an
administrative barrier than a technical one, and Stephen and I are
meeting with LTS within our first weeks back in January to define the
onboarding process. You and one other library unit are first on our list
to bring on as new users.

=20

If this all sounds satisfactory to you, I will be happy to follow up
after our meeting in January to begin the process. I hope you are well
and looking forward to a rejuvenating Winter Recess!

=20

Warmly,

Tricia

=20

